,"depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"g8k7","text":"Converting Cq values to nM stock library concentrations - NEBioCalculator","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":7,"offset":0,"length":73}],"data":{}},{"key":"720f3","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fsct","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":8,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"19ggo","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2bda9","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5lvfk","text":"If using Illumina Library Prep protocols, refer to the following Library quantification and quality control quick reference guide","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":9,"offset":65,"length":64}],"data":{}},{"key":"sns7","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"2DFF13504F8811EB85CAC124E581317F","url":"https://international.neb.com/-/media/catalog/application-notes/improved-library-quantitation-for-a-broad-range-of-library-types-e7630.pdf?rev=db57da9b1f3441c6acc804112b3e5816&hash=518F61B3B10E511C7C5504A9097A7CC5"}},"1":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"C7D58D604F8811EB85CAC124E581317F","url":"https://international.neb.com/protocols/2015/05/14/experimental-considerations-e7630"}},"2":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"E62D7F204F8811EB85CAC124E581317F","url":"https://international.neb.com/-/media/nebus/files/manuals/manuale7630.pdf?rev=2b1381e2d4ca48cc9b418ae1786afb50&hash=39DAAE7C4C73439E66CC05CD3FF67E35"}},"3":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"C0B50F104F8811EB85CAC124E581317F","url":"https://international.neb.com/protocols/2015/05/14/nebnext-library-quant-kit-quick-protocol-e7630"}},"4":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"00F063404F8911EB85CAC124E581317F","url":"https://international.neb.com/protocols/2015/05/14/nebnext-library-quant-kit-protocol-e7630"}},"5":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"F4C8F7D04F8811EB85CAC124E581317F","url":"https://international.neb.com/protocols/2015/05/14/data-analysis-e7630"}},"6":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"F96340704F8811EB85CAC124E581317F","url":"https://international.neb.com/protocols/2015/05/15/expected-results-e7630"}},"7":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"4EE22D1054C811EBBF33FD9D751EDFD2","url":"http://nebiocalculator.neb.com/#!/qPCRlibQnt"}},"8":{"type":"notes","mutability":"","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":612,"offset":0,"style":"align-justify"}],"key":"bhtjo","text":"If using a method other than qPCR to quantify your libraries, the subsequent pooling and dilution steps will be according to total molecules rather than sequenceable molecules, and these numbers may be different. This may, in turn, lead to variable representation of fragments on the flowcell. Shorter library molecules cluster more efficiently on an Illumina flowcell, so libraries with longer molecules may be underrepresented in the final counts. Moreover, sequence reads of very low quality are removed by the Illumina sequencer's software, so these clusters are not reflected in the post-filter read counts.","type":"unordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"5sduc","text":"","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":187,"offset":0,"style":"align-justify"}],"key":"1oqbo","text":"If one of the triplicates of a diluted library sample is an outlier (i.e. > 0.5 Cq from the other replicates), then the data from this outlier should be excluded from the data analysis.

","type":"unordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":354,"offset":0,"style":"align-justify"}],"key":"3e6sp","text":"For accurate quantitation, it is essential to have at least one library dilution that falls within the range of the DNA Standards 1–4. If all qPCR traces for the diluted library sample fall outside the range of the standards, then the qPCR assay should be repeated with greater (if faster than standard 1) or lower (if slower than standard 4) dilution.

","type":"unordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":529,"offset":0,"style":"align-justify"}],"key":"748t6","text":"The traces for the NTC may show unexpected amplification due to contamination of library targets, primer-dimers, or amplified products if the qPCR assays have been performed repeatedly. As long as the Cq value for the NTC is far enough away from the dynamic range of the DNA Standards (e.g. Cq of NTC should be > 30), the NTC amplification can be ignored as it will not have any effect on library quantitation. If the NTC shows faster amplification, new NEBNext Library Quant Dilution Buffer should be prepared for the next runs.","type":"unordered-list-item"}],"entityMap":{}}},"9":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"CFB42D2054CE11EB9A5D31982691DD9A","url":"https://emea.support.illumina.com/bulletins/2016/05/library-quantification-and-quality-control-quick-reference-guide.html"}}}}
